threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib64/ld-linux-x86-64.so.2, for GNU/Linux 2.6.32, BuildID[sha1]=5f18d2b1f14f60ab7de1975a867b1bbe0a3e753b, with debug_info, not stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a trojanized version of the OpenSSH server (sshd). It contains a hardcoded password backdoor ("KGQSMpuBt63M"). Upon successful authentication with any valid credentials, it logs the username and password to `/usr/include/netda.h`. If the backdoor password is used, it provides a shell, disables history logging by setting `HISTFILE` to `/dev/null`, and executes `w;uname -a`.
